## Key Configuration Points for Podman on NixOS

### Basic Podman Configuration

To enable Podman on NixOS, you can use the following configuration:

```nix
{
  virtualisation = {
    podman = {
      enable = true;
      dockerCompat = true;
      defaultNetwork.dnsname.enable = true;
    };
  };
}
```

### Rootless vs Rootful Considerations

Podman is more or less intended to be run as user, not root (rootless containers). Podman can run rootless containers and be a drop-in replacement for Docker.

#### For Rootless Setup:

1. **Important**: You have to use Home Manager for Rootless Podman containers/pods. Using systemd.user.services won't work.

2. Note that rootless podman requires newuidmap (from shadow).

3. Because students log into our lab computers using Kerberos, they don't have /etc/subuid and /etc/subgid entries automatically created for them. So, in this particular setup, we also have a pam_exec hook to create the entries for them, otherwise Podman won't work.

### Storage Driver Configuration

My root directory is btrfs and podman is using the overlay graph driver (i.e., podman info | grep graphDriverName returns graphDriverName: overlay).

For ZFS users:
Rootless can't use ZFS directly but the overlay needs POSIX ACL enabled for the underlying ZFS filesystem, ie., acltype=posixacl · Best to mount a dataset under /var/lib/containers/storage with property acltype=posixacl.

### Systemd Integration

They are each started with generated systemd units. oci-containers is a simple wrapper that generates a few systemd services and runs them as root.

For rootful containers using oci-containers:
```nix
{
  virtualisation.oci-containers.backend = "podman";
  virtualisation.oci-containers.containers = {
    container-name = {
      image = "container-image";
      autoStart = true;
      ports = [ "127.0.0.1:1234:1234" ];
    };
  };
}
```

### Rootless Configuration Example

Here's a more complete rootless configuration:

```nix
{
  config, lib, pkgs, ...
}:
{
  # Enable Podman
  virtualisation.podman = {
    enable = true;
    dockerCompat = true;
  };

  # Set DOCKER_HOST for docker-compose compatibility
  environment.sessionVariables = {
    DOCKER_HOST = "unix:///run/user/$UID/podman/podman.sock";
  };
}
```

We set the DOCKER_HOST environment variable on user login so that docker-compose works using the rootless Podman socket.

### Working Around Rootless Limitations

For running oci-containers as a specific user, you can use:
```nix
systemd.services."xxx".serviceConfig = {
  User = "xxx";
  Group = "xxx";
};
```
The problem is that the cidfile is hardcoded using this path: --cidfile=/run/podman-${escapedName}.ctr-id. So even if you change the user/pass, the user will not have permissions to write the cidfile.

### Additional Considerations

1. podman-compose is a drop-in replacement for docker-compose

2. For rootless networking issues, ensure proper user configuration with subUidRanges

3. When using btrfs with overlay storage driver, you may encounter issues with numerous subvolumes being created

